[[File:Carl Nicolai Starcke 1897.jpg|thumb|Starcke]]
'''Carl Nicolai Starcke''' (born 29 March 1858 in Copenhagen, died 7 March 1926 in Copenhagen) was a [[Danish people|Danish]] [[sociologist]], [[politician]], educator and [[philosopher]].  He is buried at [[Holmens Cemetery]]. He was the father of [[Viggo Starcke]], another writer and publisher of books such as ''Denmark in World History''.

==Life==
Starcke graduated in 1883 with a thesis on [[Ludwig Feuerbach|Feuerbach]].<ref name="denstoredanske">[http://www.denstoredanske.dk/index.php?title=Samfund%2C_jura_og_politik/Filosofi/Filosofi_i_1800-_og_1900-t./Carl_Nicolai_Starcke Den Store Danske]</ref> In 1916 he was against the resistance of Harald Høffding, a professor of philosophy at the [[University of Copenhagen]].<ref name="denstoredanske" /> His first political party he joined was [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]], a liberal party. In 1905 he co-founded the social-liberal party Venstre Det radicals. He was dissatisfied with the party and therefore started the establishment of [[Danmarks Retsforbund]] in 1919.<ref>[http://www.henrygeorge.dk/pionererne/ Den Danske Henry George Forenings pionerer]</ref> From 1913 to 1916 he was chairman of the [[Foreningen Norden|Henry George fora ingen]].

==Education==
In 1899 Starcke founded Det Danske Selskabs Skole ({{lang-en|The Danish Society School}}), the first free high school in Europe.<ref>Den Danske Henry George Forening: [http://www.henrygeorge.dk/pionererne/ Den Danske Henry George Forenings pionerer]</ref> It closed again in 1911, just 12 years after it was opened.

=="The primitive family in its origin and development"==

===Family sociology===
Starcke published a book named ''Die primitive Familie in ihrer Entstehung und Entwickelung'' in 1888. In it, he examined the social structures of different populations in Africa, Asia and Australia, and compared them with each other.

Starcke wrote about this book:
{{quote|The purpose of my work is to identify the primitive family and the ideas on which it is built, and the germs of moral growth, it contains evidence.<ref>{{cite book|last=Starcke|first=Carl Nikolai|title=Die Primitive Familie in ihrer Entstehung und Entwickelung.|year=1888|publisher=Brockhaus|pages=v}}</ref>}}

===Comparative method===
Starcke speculation turned against the construction of history and wants it by the application of the comparative method to replace.<ref>{{cite book|last=Starcke|first=Carl Nikolai|title=Die Primitive Familie in ihrer Entstehung und Entwickelung.|year=1888|publisher=Brockhaus|page=1}}</ref> He is against a misunderstanding of this method:

{{quote|Same legends and myths, like Social institutions, customs and traditions, we can not interpret this as testimony to common origin, because such similarities may be due to causes that can occur quite independently in several places and at different times into being.<ref name="Starcke1888">{{cite book|last=Starcke|first=Carl Nikolai|title=Die Primitive Familie in ihrer Entstehung und Entwickelung.|year=1888|publisher=Brockhaus|page=2}}</ref>}}

According to Starcke, the comparative method can not be a common origin, but close to the same conditions.<ref name="Starcke1888" />

===Source criticism===
He grappled with the quality of the source material, and explores the question of why authors come from the same sources to different results.<ref>{{cite book|last=Starcke|first=Carl Nikolai|title=Die Primitive Familie in ihrer Entstehung und Entwickelung.|year=1888|publisher=Brockhaus|page=3}}</ref>

Starcke distinguished four categories of sources:
*direct historical accounts of the development of a particular community during a certain period
*travel stories
*written down old laws and customs
*ancient myths and legends and archaeological reports

He points to the problem circuits to interpolate to periods for which there are no sources.<ref>{{cite book|last=Starcke|first=Carl Nikolai|title=Die Primitive Familie in ihrer Entstehung und Entwickelung.|year=1888|publisher=Brockhaus|page=4}}</ref>

