'''Cyrus Hamlin''' (January 5, 1811 &ndash; August 8, 1900)<ref>{{Cite book |last=  |first=  |author-link=|year= 1900 |editor-last= Leonard  |editor-first= John. W.|contribution= |title= WHO'S WHO IN AMERICA; A Biographical Dictionary of Living Men and Women of the United States 1899-1900|edition= 1|publisher= A.N. Marquis & Company  |publication-place=Chicago |page=306 |url=https://archive.org/stream/whoswhoinameric01marqgoog#page/n347/mode/2up |accessdate= September 1, 2018|via=Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www3.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=24397455 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-01-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305024734/http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=24397455 |archivedate=2016-03-05 |df= }}</ref> was an American [[Congregational church|Congregational]] [[missionary]] and educator, the father of [[Alfred Dwight Foster Hamlin|A. D. F. Hamlin]].<ref>{{cite book|last= Wright, Jr. |first= Walter L.   |editor= Malone, Dumas |editor-link= Dumas Malone |title=Dictionary of American Biography |publisher= Charles Scribner's Sons |location=New York |volume=8 (Grinnell-Hibbard) |year=1932 |chapter= Hamlin, Cyrus |url=https://archive.org/stream/dictionaryofamer08ilamer#page/195/mode/1up|pages=195-196   |accessdate=September 1, 2018|via= Internet Archive }}</ref> 

== Biography ==

Hamlin was born in [[Waterford, Maine]] and grew up on his family's farm estate. At sixteen, he entered an apprenticeship as a silversmith and jeweler in [[Portland, Maine]] before deciding to enter the ministry.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/mylifetimes00haml |last=Hamlin |first=Cyrus |title=My Life and Times|year= 1893 |page= 47}}</ref> He first attended Bridgton Academy before heading to college. He graduated from [[Bowdoin College]] in 1834 and from [[Bangor Theological Seminary]] in 1837.  The Hamlins were a prominent nineteenth-century [[Maine]] family which also produced a [[Vice President of the United States]] ([[Hannibal Hamlin]]) and at least two Civil War generals, one of whom was also named Cyrus Hamlin.

He promptly left the United States in 1838 as a [[missionary]] under the [[American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions]], arriving in the Ottoman Empire in January 1839. Hamlin helped found [[Bebek Seminary]] in 1840 as part of his outreach to Armenians.<ref>My Life and Times, p. 479-484.</ref> Hamlin established a workshop at Bebek to teach his students marketable trades, to help alleviate their severe poverty.<ref>My Life and Times, p. 257</ref> From this workshop sprung a baking business, by which Hamlin became the primary provider of bread to the British Army hospital in Istanbul during the [[Crimean War]].<ref>My Life and Times, p. 324-329</ref> It was during this period that Hamlin became acquainted with [[Florence Nightingale]].<ref>My Life and Times, p. 332-336</ref> While the workshop and bakery were controversial to the American Board, the funds earned by Hamlin's enterprises helped build thirteen Protestant Armenian churches in Turkey.<ref>My Life and Times, p. 372</ref>

In 1860, he began the work of establishing [[Robert College]] in [[Constantinople]], [[Ottoman Empire]]. After years of unsuccessfully lobbying the Ottoman authorities for permission to build the school, Hamlin was eventually granted an imperial order granting permission for the school to be built and permitting it to be under American (United States) protection and fly the flag of the [[United States of America]]. The school opened its doors on May 15, 1871.<ref>My Life and Times, p. 448-469</ref> Hamlin served as its president until an unfortunate conflict in 1876, which forced his return to the United States where he later served as professor of dogmatic theology at [[Bangor Theological Seminary]].

He was elected president of [[Middlebury College]] in [[Vermont]] in 1880. His term was short, lasting only until 1885. However, Hamlin's guidance brought the College back from the brink of collapse and began a recovery process that would ultimately lead to unprecedented growth in the early years of the 20th Century. Hamlin resolved severe disciplinary issues inherited from his predecessor and personally contracted critical upgrades to the physical plant. However, the most significant event of Hamlin's administration—one that would prove key in maintaining Middlebury's stability later on—was the college's decision to accept women in 1883. Hamlin was seventy-four by 1885 when he unsurprisingly retired.<ref>{{cite book | last=Stameshkin | first=David M. | title=The Town's College: Middlebury College 1800-1915 | publisher= Middlebury College Press | year=1985}}</ref>

He published ''Among the Turks'' (1878) and ''My Life and Times'' (1893).<ref>{{Cite book |last= Hamlin |first=Cyrus |year=1877 |title=Among the Turks |publisher=American Tract Society |place=New York |edition= 1 |page= |url=https://archive.org/stream/amongturks00hamluoft#page/n5/mode/2up|accessdate=20 March 2016 |via= Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last= Hamlin |first=Cyrus |year=1893 |title= My Life and Times |publisher=The Pilgrim Press |place=Chicago |edition= 5 |page= |url=https://archive.org/stream/mylifetimes1912haml#page/n3/mode/2up|accessdate=20 March 2016}} via Internet Archive</ref> Hamlin Hall at [[Boğaziçi University]] (formerly part of [[Robert College]]), as well as Hamlin Hall in [[Middlebury College]]'s Freeman International Center are named after him.

For many years, he lived in [[Lexington, Massachusetts]]. He is buried in Lexington's Munroe Cemetery.

